**The Problem** This study focuses on factors that may explain dog behaviour, using data from Ien Fishman, based on Stanley Coren's original work. The outcome variable is the probability of a dog breed obeying at the first command, ranging from 0 to 1. The predictors are: (1) mean height (inches), (2) mean weight (lbs), and (3) breed category according to the American Kennel Club. The aim is to estimate regression coefficients and precisions, and perform model selection and testing, while comparing frequentist and Bayesian methods. I chose to delete missing values, in applied research it is preferable to deal with missingness (for example multiple imputation).

**The Model** Given that the outcome variable was limited to 0 – 1, and there was just one measure per breed (no repeated trials), I performed beta regression. This model assumes that the observed outcome follows a beta distribution: $Y_i \sim \text{Beta}(\mu_i \phi, (1 - \mu_i) \phi)$, with density $p(y|\alpha,\beta) = \frac{\Gamma(\alpha+\beta)}{\Gamma(\alpha)\Gamma(\beta)}y^{\alpha-1}(1-y)^{\beta-1}$, where $\alpha = \mu_i * \phi$,  $\beta = \phi * (1 - \mu_i)$. To scale the linear combination of predictors with $\mu_i$, I used a logit link: $\text{logit}(\mu_i) = \log\left( \frac{\mu_i}{1 - \mu_i} \right) =\beta_0 + \beta_1 \cdot \text{MeanHeight}_i + \ldots + \beta_8 \cdot\text{CategoryWorking}_i$ (Cribari-Neto & Zeileis, 2010), so that the mean is $\mu_i = \frac{\exp(x_i^\top \beta)}{1 + \exp(x_i^\top \beta)}$ and the precision $\phi > 0$  – inverse measure of variance where higher values of $\phi$ indicate lower variance for a given $\mu_i$ (Branscum et al., 2007). In standard beta regression, $\phi$ is constant across observations assuming that all $Y_i$ have equal dispersion around their mean $\mu_i$ (this is used in the estimation part); in extended beta regression $\phi_i$ can be modelled as a function of the covariates (which I will explore in the testing part). I specified a reference category (herding dogs) and mean-centered the height and weight variables, where I first calculated a mean per breed (I only had the upper and lower bound per breed), and then centered this around the grand mean of all breeds taken together, for interpretation. 

**Frequentist Estimation** I used the package {betareg} in R (Kosmidis & Zeileis, 2024) to get point estimates of $\mu_i$ and $\phi$ using maximum likelihood (MLE). I evaluated convergence using built-in {betareg} functions, which returned a convergence code of 0, indicating successful MLE convergence. In addition, I used residual plots to assess model fit. Observation 20 was potentially influential, as it showed a large Cook’s distance. When refitting the model without it, the coefficients and $\phi$ remained almost unchanged, suggesting a robust model. The residuals-vs-indices plot showed a downward slope, which was expected given that the data were ordered by the obey variable; after shuffling, residuals seemed randomly scattered around zero. The residuals-vs-linear-predictors plot showed a curvilinear clustered pattern (no random scatter), indicating a possibly incorrect assumption of constant $\phi$ across predictors. After specifying $\phi_i$ to vary, the residual plot was scattered randomly.

**Bayesian Estimation – Metropolis-Hastings Sampler**
To estimate the posterior distribution of the parameters in my beta regression model (which doesn't have a conjugate prior when a logit-link is used), I programmed a Metropolis–Hastings (MH) Markov Chain Monte Carlo (MCMC) sampler, with 10.000 iterations. Based on Inglis et al. (2018), I evaluated the likelihood $\mathcal{L}(y \mid \mu_i, \phi) = \prod_{i=1}^{n} \frac{\Gamma(\phi)}{\Gamma(\mu_i\phi)\Gamma((1 - \mu_i)\phi)} \cdot y_i^{\mu_i \phi - 1} (1 - y_i)^{(1 - \mu_i)\phi - 1}$, as a log-likelihood to increase numerical stability and simplify of the MH-algorithm: $\log \mathcal{L}(y \mid \mu_i, \phi) = \sum_{i=1}^{n} \left[\log \Gamma(\phi) - \log \Gamma(\mu_i \phi) - \log \Gamma((1 - \mu_i) \phi)+ (\mu_i \phi - 1)\log y_i + ((1 - \mu_i) \phi - 1) \log (1 - y_i)\right]$. I used weakly informative priors $\beta_j\sim \mathcal{N}(0, 1)$ – each $\beta_j$ was updated conditionally on the other coefficients $\beta_{j-1}$), the data (y), and $\phi$. For $\phi$, I used $\phi \sim \text{Gamma}(1,0.01)$ as a prior, since this parameter should be positive. I evaluated the priors at a log-scale: $\log p(\beta_j) = -\frac{1}{2} \log(2\pi \sigma^2) - \frac{1}{2} \left(\frac{\beta_j - \mu}{\sigma} \right)^2$, where $\log p(\beta) = \sum_{j=1}^{k} \log p(\beta_j)$, assuming independent normal priors for all $\beta_j$; $\log p(\phi) = \alpha \log(\beta) - \log\Gamma(\alpha) + (\alpha -1)\log(\phi) - \beta \phi$ *Note:* $\beta$ *in this case is the rate parameter, not a regression coefficient*. 
Instead of a conjugate prior, MH-sampling makes use of a proposal distributions. For $\beta_j$ I used a (symmetric) normal random walk: $\beta_j^* \sim \beta_j^{t-1} + \epsilon$, where $\epsilon \sim \mathcal{N}(0, \sigma_j^2)$. For $\phi$, I used a gamma distribution, centred around $\phi^{t-1}$: $\phi^* \sim\text{Gamma}\left(\frac{(\phi^{(t-1)})^2}{\sigma_\phi^2}, \text{rate} = \frac{\phi^{(t-1)}}{\sigma_\phi^2} \right)$. The proposal variances $\sigma_j^2$ and $\sigma_\phi^2$ were adjusted each iteration during the burn-in period (2000 iterations), to make sure the acceptance-rate as close within the range of 20%-40% as possible. 
The goal of this MH-sampler is to approximate the joint posterior $p(\beta, \phi \mid y) \propto \mathcal{L}(y \mid \boldsymbol{\beta}, \phi) \cdot p(\boldsymbol{\beta}) \cdot p(\phi)$, by iteratively sampling from the full conditional posteriors of each parameter, where $p(\beta_j \mid \beta_{-j}, \phi, y) = \mathcal{L}(y \mid \beta_{-j}, \phi) \cdot p(\beta_j)$ and $p(\phi \mid \beta, y) = \mathcal{L}(y \mid \beta, \phi) \cdot p(\phi)$. Since the proposal distribution for $\beta^*$ is symmetric, the acceptance ratio was calculated as: $r = \frac{p(y \mid \beta_j^*, \phi) \cdot p(\beta_j^*)}{p(y \mid \beta_j^{t-1}, \phi) \cdot p(\beta_j^{t-1})}$. The proposal distribution for $\phi^*$ is not symmetric, so the proposal distribution is taken into account in r to make sure it is unbiased: $r = \frac {p(y \mid \beta,\phi^*) \cdot p(\phi^*)}{p(y \mid \beta,\phi^{t-1}) \cdot p(\phi^{t-1})}\cdot \frac{q(\phi^{t-1}\mid \phi^*)}{q(\phi^*\mid \phi^{t-1})}$. These values are compared to a random sample from a uniform distribution $U \sim\mathcal{U}(0, 1)$, if $r > U \rightarrow \beta_j = \beta^*$, if $r < U \rightarrow \beta_j = \beta^{t-1}$. 
After the burn-in period, I calculated posterior means of the samples from the posterior distributions of $\beta$ and $\phi$, and used these as point estimates; 95%-credible intervals were calculated by taking the 2.5th and 97.5th percentiles the sampled values. 

**Bayesian Estimation – Stan**
For comparison, I also performed Bayesian estimation using Stan, with the {brms} package, which uses the No-U-Turn Sampler (NUTS), a variant of Hamiltonian Monte Carlo (HMC), relying on a different sampling algorithm than Metropolis–Hastings. I used 10,000 iterations with a 2,000 iteration burn-in, and specified the same priors as in my MH-sampler: $\beta_j \sim \mathcal{N}(0, 1)$ and $\phi \sim \text{Gamma}(1, 0.01)$. Stan evaluates these priors on the log-scale by default.

