To evaluate convergence of both samplers, I used trace plots, autocorrelation plots (ACF), and acceptance rates. As shown in Figure 1, the trace plots for all MH-sampled $\beta_j$ show medium well mixing: in every iteration the sample moves to a new place on the posterior, but with small steps.That of $\phi$ is much better, suggesting good convergence of this parameter. It stands out that in the Stan trace plot, all parameters seem to have converged well. In the MH-ACF plots most $\beta_j$ curves decline slowly and remain outside the significance boundaries (blue lines), indicating that the $\beta_j$ samples are highly correlated with previous samples — more iterations are necessary for more effective convergence. In contrast, the MH-ACF for $\phi$ drops quickly, suggesting better mixing for $\phi$. In the Stan-ACF, there appears to be low autocorrelation for all parameters. Acceptance rates for the MH-sampled parameters were high for most $\beta_j$: $\beta_0$: 0.77, $\beta_1$: 0.42, $\beta_2$: 0.18, $\beta_3$–$\beta_8$: between 0.89 and 0.92. Only $\beta_1$ and $\beta_2$ fall within the recommended range (0.1 – 0.6; Lai, 2019). The acceptance rate for $\phi$ was 0.41, meaning 41% of proposed values were accepted — consistent with its low autocorrelation. High acceptance rates lead to small proposal steps, which cause high autocorrelation. In conclusion, based on the trace plots, acceptance rates and ACF, all parameters  — except $\phi$ — in my MH-sampler clearly show higher autocorrelation and less efficiency than those from Stan. This implies that NUTS-sampling is more efficient than MH-sampling, and more iterations or better tuning are needed in my MH-sampler to improve sampling efficiency.

