To highlight the differences between frequentist and Bayesian estimation, I decided to plot all estimates with weak priors, but I also added a second Bayesian estimation (both MH and Stan) where I used more informative/stronger priors: $\beta_j \sim \mathcal{N}(3,0.5)$ and $\phi \sim \text{Gamma}(1,0.8)$. 

**Behind The Estimates** It stands out that the estimates and uncertainty intervals of the frequentist method and both Bayesian methods with weak priors overlap almost entirely, emphasizing the heavy reliance on the data in both cases. However, when strong priors are used, it is clear that most estimates — and their substantive conclusions — differ strongly between frequentist and Bayesian methods. This way, one of the key differences between the two methods is emphasizes: where frequentists *only* rely on the data, Bayesian inference reflects both the likelihood (probability of the data) and the prior. When using a strong prior for $\beta_j$, distributed around a mean of 3, the posterior mean estimates are pulled towards that value. In the case of $\phi$, when a stronger prior was used (lower variance around shape = 1), the posterior estimate of $\phi$ was much lower, showing it was pulled towards 1 by the prior. Interestingly, this influence of the prior was not observed for weight and height, where all methods — regardless of how strong the prior was — seem to result in more or less the same estimates with a very narrow uncertainty interval. This suggests that the data are sufficient to explain the effect of these predictors, making reliance on the prior relatively unnecessary.

It stood out to me that no matter how strong the prior, when the data provide enough evidence, the posterior distribution seems to align with the likelihood, while 'ignoring' the prior; and when the data are not informative, as was the case with Category, the strong prior has a larger influence. This actually makes a lot of sense when looking at Bayes' theorem; by multiplying the likelihood and the prior, the 'strongest' (highest peak) distribution has most weight. This shows that Bayesian estimation is not about simply 'adding some prior that changes everything immediately' (as some frequentists may like to claim), but is actually a more nuanced way to visualise the 'strength' of the evidence of the data — a feature that standard frequentist estimation lacks.

Although most of the estimates seem to overlap numerically, is important to highlight the underlying philosophical differences when interpreting these results. It should be noted that the frequentist estimates are *point estimates* of maximum likelihood estimates, which are assumed to be fixed variables; Bayesian estimates, on the other hand, are summary statistics, in this case the *mean of a full posterior distribution*, which are assumed to be random variables — meaning it quantifies uncertainty and is not just one static estimate.

**Substantive Interpretation Estimates** The frequentist point estimate for the intercept $\beta_0$ was 1.24 (SE = 0.27, p < 0.01), indicating that herding dogs of average height (19.53 inches) and weight (47.63 lbs) have an estimated probability of 0.78 of obeying the first command. In the Bayesian MH model, the posterior mean of $\beta_0$ was 0.92, corresponding to a 0.72 probability of obedience for average herding dogs — representing the expected value of this probability based on the posterior distribution (e.g. after combining prior beliefs with the observed data). Based on Stan, the posterior mean of $\beta_0$ was 0.97, so average herding dogs had a probability of about 0.73 to obey. When using a strong prior, the posterior means of MH and Stan were -0.98 and -1.93, which equals obey probabilities of 0.27 and 0.13, which is completely different.

Across frequentist and weak-prior Bayesian estimation, hounds, non-sporting dogs, terriers and toy dogs had significantly lower log-odds of obeying at the first command than herding dogs (see Figure 2). When using strong priors, the effects of Category were reversed, where all other dog breeds had significantly higher log-odds to obey than herding dogs (see Figure 2 for approximate estimates).

In the frequentist and weak-prior Bayesian models, $\phi$ was estimated to have a value around 6, indication low dispersion around the predicted obedience probabilities — dogs with similar values for the predictors had relatively similar obedience probabilities. In the strong-prior Bayesian models, $\phi$ was smaller, indicating more variance in obedience probability.

**Quantification of Uncertainty** Not only the interpretation of the estimates differs between methods, there are also philosophical differences in the quantification of uncertainty. In frequentist estimation, the 95%-confidence interval is defined as "if this research was repeated $n \rightarrow \infty$ times, 95% of those intervals would contain the true parameter value". In Bayesian estimation, the uncertainty is as a 95%-credible interval, which quantifies one's belief that, given the data and the prior, there is a probability of 95% that the true parameter value falls within this range.

*Note: Not only do the meaning of estimates and quantification of uncertainty differ between frequentist and Bayesian estimation — their definition of probability does too! This means that "the probability of obedience" does not refer to the same thing in the two types of inference. For frequentists, it would mean 'the proportion of times out of N identical repetitions a dog would obey at the first command', while for Bayesians it would mean 'my belief that this dog would obey at the first command, based on the data and my prior knowledge'.*

